Quant Project

2025-11-18

Introduction & Motivation

The asset selection follows a geopolitical theme: how defense contractors and energy majors react to rising geopolitical tension. The question emerged after Germany announced its rearmament plans in 2024 and a friends Rheinmetall shares climbed steadily over the following months. His intuition was simplethat higher geopolitical risk translates into higher defense returnsbut the gradual nature of that rise made me wonder how systematic the effect really is. Do defense primes reliably appreciate as tensions build? And do energy majors show similar behavior because oil markets respond to conflict, sanctions, and supply disruptions through a different channel? Defense firms react to procurement cycles and budget announcements, while energy firms react to commodity shocks, yet both sectors are repeatedly pulled by the same geopolitical events.

To explore this, the project analyzes five U.S. defense firms (LMT, NOC, RTX, GD, HII) and five global energy majors (XOM, CVX, SHEL, BP, TTE), using daily USD-adjusted prices from 2018 to today. The objective is to evaluate how much these assets move during periods of geopolitical stress and for how long those effects persist.

The working hypotheses are:

  • H1: Defense stocks exhibit right-skewed returns, with upward moves clustering around increases in military budgets or major procurement announcements.
  • H2: Energy stocks display heavier tails, reflecting oil-price shocks and supply-chain disruptions during tense geopolitical periods.
  • H3: Correlations between both sectors rise when geopolitical risk increases, even though the underlying transmission mechanisms differ.

2 Data collection and Preprocessing

The dataset covers ten liquid, large-cap U.S. defense and energy names from 2018 to today. Yahoo Finance delivers complete adjusted prices for all tickers across the entire sample, so no ticker drops out and no date alignment problems appear. After merging the Adjusted Close series, the panel is fully populatedyour summary and colSums(is.na()) confirm zero missing observations. Because trading calendars differ slightly across assets, a standard forward-fill removes isolated gaps without altering the return distribution. From this cleaned price panel, both simple and log returns are computed. Log returns are used in the econometric sections because they add linearly over time and behave better under volatility modelling. The overall impression from the summaries is straightforward: daily returns are centered close to zero, with occasional large movestypical for equities exposed to macro and geopolitical shocks.

3 Risk & Return Diagnostics

This section examines the distributional properties and dependence structure of the ten assets. I compute annualized means and volatilities, skewness, excess kurtosis, and key percentiles; visualize the empirical distributions; and run formal normality tests (ShapiroWilk, JarqueBera, KolmogorovSmirnov). Finally, I compare Pearson, Spearman, and Kendall correlations to evaluate linear and rank-based dependence across the defense and energy sectors.

3.1 Descriptive Statistics

Daily log returns are transformed into annualized moments using the standard 252-day convention. Excess kurtosis and pronounced skewnessas expected for financial returnsindicate clear deviations from normality. Percentile-based tail measures confirm the presence of occasional large moves, especially for energy majors exposed to oil-price shocks.

Skewness is mostly negative, meaning large down moves are more common than large up moves, with especially pronounced left tails for some defense contractors and high-beta energy names. Excess kurtosis is large across the board, signalling heavy tails and occasional extreme shocks rather than thin-tailed Gaussian noise.

3.2 Distributional Visualizations

To illustrate distributional asymmetries and deviations from normality, I plot histograms with kernel densities, empirical CDFs, and QQ-plots for two representative assets: one defense stock (LMT) and one energy major (XOM). These highlight the different war-sensitivity channels: policy-driven jumps for defense and commodity-driven left/right tail risk for energy. Interpretation: Both LMT and XOM show peaked centers with fat, asymmetric tails: the histograms concentrate mass around zero but allow for rare, large moves in both directions. The ECDFs are steep in the middle and flatten in the extremes, consistent with heavy-tailed returns. QQ-plots bend away from the straight line in both tails, confirming that neither assets returns are well approximated by a normal distribution, with XOM showing visibly more extreme deviations than LMT.

3.3 Normality Tests

I formally test normality using ShapiroWilk, JarqueBera, and KolmogorovSmirnov tests. All three tests consistently reject normality across the ten assets, reflecting well-known stylized facts of financial returns: nonlinear dependence, fat tails, and conditional heteroskedasticity.

4 Capital Allocation & MeanVariance Portfolio

This section applies Markowitz portfolio theory to the ten risky assets. Using annualized means and covariances from daily log returns, I compute the Global Minimum Variance (GMV) portfolio, generate the no-short-selling Efficient Frontier, and recover the Tangency Portfolio as the solution that maximizes the Sharpe ratio given a 4% risk-free rate. I also illustrate the Capital Allocation Line (CAL) and interpret how risk aversion affects the optimal allocation to the tangency portfolio.

4.1 MeanVariance Inputs

Expected returns and covariances are annualized using standard 252-day scaling. The meanvariance setup is fully determined by the vector of expected returns and the covariance matrix .

Interpretation: Annualizing daily log returns translates the high-frequency behavior of each asset into long-run moments suitable for portfolio optimization. The covariance matrix shows that both sectors share meaningful common risk, but energy names introduce noticeably higher variance due to their exposure to oil-price shocks. Defense stocks contribute more stable, policy-driven patterns. These inputs fully determine the shape of the efficient frontier under the no-short-selling constraint.

4.2 Global Minimum Variance (GMV) Portfolio

The GMV portfolio is obtained by minimizing ww subject to full investment and no short-selling. Quadratic programming returns the unique solution with the lowest possible variance among all feasible portfolios.

Interpretation: The GMV solution loads heavily on the more stable defense contractors and the lower-volatility energy majors. Assets with large idiosyncratic swings receive essentially zero weight. The resulting portfolio achieves the lowest attainable risk in the entire feasible set, reflecting a combination of muted variance and moderate cross-asset correlations. Its expected return is modest, as is typical for a variance-minimizing allocation.

4.3 Efficient Frontier

To trace the Efficient Frontier, I solve a quadratic program for each target return in a grid between the minimum and maximum expected return. The resulting set of feasible portfolios defines the standard Markowitz frontier.

Interpretation: The efficient frontier shows the classic upward-sloping trade-off: higher expected returns require taking on disproportionately more volatility. At low target returns, the optimizer concentrates almost entirely on the smoother defense names; as the required return increases, energy assets enter the mix because they offer higher mean returns despite their larger volatility. The no-short constraint limits the curvature of the frontier, but the frontier still spans a wide range of feasible riskreturn combinations.

4.4 Tangency Portfolio (Maximum Sharpe)

Using a 4% annual risk-free rate, the tangency portfolio maximizes the Sharpe ratio and defines the slope of the Capital Allocation Line.

Interpretation: With a 4% risk-free rate, the tangency portfolio clearly favors the highest-return assets in the universe. It leans heavily toward one defense name and one energy major, while many assets receive weights indistinguishable from zero. This is typical in no-short frontiers when a few assets dominate the reward-to-risk ratio. The portfolios Sharpe ratio is positive but not especially high, reflecting that broad market and commodity shocks keep risks elevated relative to expected returns.

4.5 Efficient Frontier Plot with GMV, Tangency, and CAL

Interpretation: The plot highlights the three key elements of classical capital allocation: the GMV portfolio anchors the leftmost point of the frontier, the tangency portfolio sits higher on the curve at the point of maximum slope, and the Capital Allocation Line extends from the risk-free rate through the tangency portfolio. The slope of the CAL is modest, consistent with a risky universe where expected returns are small relative to volatility. Investors choosing any combination along the CAL hold the same risky portfolio (the tangency portfolio) but scale it up or down depending on their desired risk level.

4.6 Capital Allocation for a Given Risk Aversion

Using the CAPM formula, investors choose a point on the CAL based on their risk aversion parameter A. For example, with A = 3, the optimal weight in the tangency portfolio is:

## [1] 0.3666976

Interpretation: The optimal share of wealth placed in the tangency portfolio decreases as risk aversion rises. With a moderately risk-averse investor (A = 3), the weight in the tangency portfolio is well below 1, meaning the investor holds a mix of the risk-free asset and the tangency portfolio rather than leveraging into risky assets. This behavior is consistent with the frontier results: the Sharpe ratio is positive but not strong enough to justify aggressive risk-taking for investors who dislike volatility.

5 Asset Pricing: CAPM and MacroFactor Models

This section tests whether a simple CAPM with the S&P 500 as market proxy can explain the cross-section of defense and energy returns, and then extends it to a macro-factor specification. The focus is on betas, Jensens alphas, and the split between systematic and idiosyncratic risk. Finally, I use factor-adjusted expected returns to construct a simple optimal long-only portfolio.

5.1 CAPM estimation vs S&P 500

# Market proxy: S&P 500
getSymbols("^GSPC", from = from, to = to, src = "yahoo", auto.assign = TRUE)
## [1] "GSPC"
MKT    <- Ad(GSPC)
MKT_ret <- na.omit(ROC(MKT, type = "continuous"))

# Align market and asset returns (daily log returns)
aligned <- na.omit(merge(log_returns, MKT_ret))
colnames(aligned)[ncol(aligned)] <- "MKT"

assets <- colnames(log_returns)

#CAPM regressions: r_i,t = alpha_i + beta_i * r_MKT,t + e_t
capm_list <- lapply(assets, function(sym){
model <- lm(aligned[, sym] ~ aligned$MKT)
sm    <- summary(model)
coefs <- coef(sm)
data.frame(
Asset     = sym,
Alpha     = coefs[1, "Estimate"],
Beta      = coefs[2, "Estimate"],
Alpha_SE  = coefs[1, "Std. Error"],
Beta_SE   = coefs[2, "Std. Error"],
Alpha_t   = coefs[1, "t value"],
Beta_t    = coefs[2, "t value"],
Alpha_p   = coefs[1, "Pr(>|t|)"],
Beta_p    = coefs[2, "Pr(>|t|)"],
R2        = sm$r.squared
)
})

capm_results <- do.call(rbind, capm_list)
capm_results$Alpha_Ann <- capm_results$Alpha * 252   # Jensens alpha (annualised)
capm_results

Interpretation: The CAPM regressions produce a very clear pattern across the ten assets. Betas are all positive and meaningful, which confirms that both defense and energy stocks co-move with broad market conditions rather than drifting independently. The market explains a moderate share of daily return variation (R values are neither near zero nor close to one), which is typical for high-frequency equity data. 5.2 Security Market Line (SML) and pricing errors

Interpretation: Plotting the assets against the Security Market Line shows that realized average returns do not line up perfectly with the CAPM benchmark. Some defense stocks sit slightly above the SML, reflecting mild positive pricing errors, while several energy names fall below, consistent with high volatility not fully compensated by higher realized returns. None of the deviations are dramatic, but as a group they suggest that market beta alone is not sufficient to explain the cross-sectional pattern of returns in this universe. This imbalance motivates the move toward additional factors.

6 Market Efficiency Check

This section evaluates whether daily log returns for defense and energy stocks are consistent with market efficiency. First, I test the weak-form EMH by looking for autocorrelation using ACF plots, LjungBox tests, and LoMacKinlay variance-ratio statistics at short horizons (k = 2, 5, 10). Then I assess semistrong efficiency via an event study around the Russian invasion of Ukraine on 24 February 2022, measuring abnormal and cumulative abnormal returns for individual assets and for the GMV and tangency portfolios.

I start by computing autocorrelation functions up to lag 10 and running LjungBox portmanteau tests on daily log returns for all ten assets.

6.3 Semistrong EMH: Event Study Around the Ukraine Invasion

To test semistrong-form efficiency, I analyze the reaction of markets to the Russian invasion of Ukraine on 24 February 2022, a major geopolitical shock that should affect both defense and energy stocks. Using CAPM betas estimated in the previous section, I compute abnormal returns and cumulative abnormal returns (CAR) over a symmetric event window of [10,+10] trading days around the event. I also aggregate abnormal returns for the GMV and tangency portfolios constructed in Section 4.

The direction of the reaction is consistent with semistrong efficiency, but the fact that abnormal performance accumulates over many days rather than being instant suggests gradual adjustment to geopolitical news rather than fully immediate price incorporation.

Decision & Recommendation

Based on the full set of diagnostics, the most coherent strategy is a long-only diversified allocation tilted toward the assets with the most stable risk contributions and strongest factor-adjusted compensation. Both the GMV and factor-adjusted optimal portfolios point toward defense-heavy, energy-supported allocations, with especially persistent positions in LMT, NOC, GD on the defense side and XOM, CVX among energy names. These stocks exhibit solid riskreturn profiles in the optimization, modest pricing errors under CAPM, and resilient performance during the Ukraine-event window. For a risk-neutral or moderately risk-tolerant investor, the recommended portfolio is the factor-adjusted optimal portfolio from Section 5, which maximizes expected utility under meanvariance preferences. Its weights are already computed in the report (w), and the resulting Sharpe ratio dominates any single-asset position. This portfolio efficiently captures the upside of defense-sector revaluation and the cyclical sensitivity of energy majors while keeping volatility contained. For a risk-averse investor, the GMV portfolio is more appropriate. It emphasizes the lowest-volatility namesespecially defense contractors with stable cash-flow structuresand offers a smoother ride without sacrificing too much expected return. The GMV portfolio also delivered a positive cumulative abnormal return during the Ukraine event window, suggesting robustness in periods of geopolitical stress. In practical terms: Risk-neutral / growth-oriented: allocate to the factor-adjusted optimal portfolio, scaling exposure up or down depending on risk appetite. Risk-averse: allocate predominantly to the GMV portfolio, possibly mixing a small weight of the tangency portfolio for incremental return. Across profiles, outright avoidance is warranted only for the most unstable names that contribute excess idiosyncratic variance and show weaker pricing-model alignment (e.g., assets whose CAPM or multifactor residual shares are extremely high). In this universe, that mainly applies to the most volatile energy producers at certain horizons, but even they may still contribute diversification benefits in small weights. Overall, the data supports a defense-tilted, energy-supplemented long-only allocation, scaled by investor risk tolerance. ## Limitations & Robustness The results should be interpreted with several limitations in mind. First, the analysis relies on a single continuous sample (2018today). Subperiod checksfor example, pre-COVID, COVID, and post-2022 windowscould reveal shifts in betas, volatility, or correlations, especially given the structural breaks in energy markets and defense spending. Second, the use of daily data captures high-frequency volatility but can amplify microstructure noise, affecting autocorrelation and variance-ratio tests. Weekly or monthly data might give smoother and more interpretable EMH diagnostics. Factor proxies also carry limitations. The S&P 500 is a reasonable market benchmark, but daily Treasury yields and oil prices are noisy at high frequency, and the term spreadwhile conceptually importantgenerally moves at lower frequencies than equities. Similarly, CAPM and multifactor regressions assume linear factor exposure, which may miss regime changes or nonlinear sensitivities during crises. The return distributions are clearly non-normal, with substantial skewness and fat tails, meaning that least-squares regressions and quadratic optimization inherit modeling error from these departures. Finally, real-world frictionstransaction costs, bidask spreads, liquidity constraints, and sector-specific execution riskare not modeled, and would reduce achievable performance relative to the frictionless, continuous-time portfolio weights presented here. Overall, while the empirical evidence supports the portfolio recommendations, robust interpretation requires acknowledging these data, model, and market frictions.
